<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>Report:</head><p>Sodium cobaltate (Na x CoO 2 ) has emerged as a material of exceptional technological interest due to its potential for thermoelectric applications <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1,</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b1">2]</ref>, and our neutron diffraction studies have demonstrated the central role played by superstructures <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref>.</p><p>A single crystal of Na 0.8 CoO 2 in the ordered stripe phase <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref> was mounted on ID28 on a glass needle in two orientations: with (h0l) and (hhl) horizontal scattering planes. The phonon dispersion was measured along several symmetry directions and at many general wave-vector transfers, Q. Figure <ref type="figure" target="#fig_0">1</ref> shows typical data, in this case for the dispersion measured along ΓΚ. The agreement with a calculation for NaCoO 2 using the CASTEP code is very promising.</p><p>Preliminary calculations for Na 0.8 CoO 2 with the ordered stripe phase indicate that there is a Q-independent rattler mode at E ~ 12 meV. Figure <ref type="figure" target="#fig_1">2</ref> shows experimental evidence for this extra mode in our data, with the correct temperature factor. This is an important result since the rattling of cations is expected to disrupt the propogation of phonons, leading to low thermal conductivity, as required for optimum thermoelectric performance.</p><p>Figure <ref type="figure" target="#fig_2">3</ref> shows the temperature dependence of an acoustic phonon at T ~ 200 K in the ordered stripe phase, at T ~ 320 K in a partially disordered stripe phase, and at T ~ 400 K in the disordered phase. There is some broadening and softening of this phonon at elevated temperatures, but the effects are subtle.   </p></div><figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_0"><head>Fig. 1 .</head><label>1</label><figDesc>Fig. 1. One of the phonon dispersions along ΓΚ measured on ID28 (red circles). The data agree well with calculations forNaCoO 2 using the CASTEP code (intensity contour diagram).</figDesc><graphic coords="2,66.95,50.75,303.00,216.60" type="bitmap" /></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_1"><head>Fig. 2 .</head><label>2</label><figDesc>Fig. 2. A rattler mode was observed at E ~ 12 meV, in agreement with preliminary CASTEP calculations using the ordered stripe phase superstructure for Na 0.8 CoO 2 .</figDesc><graphic coords="2,220.20,287.05,294.95,208.45" type="bitmap" /></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_2"><head>Fig. 3 .</head><label>3</label><figDesc>Fig. 3. An acoustic phonon in the ordered stripe phase (blue), a partially disordered stripe phase (yellow) and the disordered phase (red), showing broadening and softening as a function of temperature.</figDesc><graphic coords="2,66.95,515.75,271.95,202.95" type="bitmap" /></figure>
		</body>
